{"title_page": "Black-headed greenfinch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Chloris ambigua, captive.jpg\n| name = Black-headed greenfinch\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |author=BirdLife International |title=''Chloris ambigua'' |volume=2016 |page=e.T22720347A94665586 |date=2016 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22720347A94665586.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Chloris\n| species = ambigua\n| authority = ([[\u00c9mile Oustalet|Oustalet]], 1896)\n| synonyms = ''Carduelis ambigua''\n}}\n\nThe '''black-headed greenfinch''' (''Chloris ambigua'') is a small [[passerine]] bird in the family [[Fringillidae]].\nIt is found in the Chinese province of [[Yunnan]], northern [[Laos]], eastern [[Myanmar]] and adjacent areas of [[Vietnam]], [[Thailand]] and [[Northeast India]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are [[subtropical or tropical dry forest]] and [[subtropical or tropical dry shrubland]].\n\nThe black-headed greenfinch is a medium-sized finch with a length of {{cvt|12.4|-|14|cm}}. It has a dark blackish-olive head, a pale pinkish-brown conical bill and a yellow patch on the wings. The sexes are similar.<ref name=hbw>{{cite web | last=Clement | first=P. | year=2017 | title=Black-headed Greenfinch (''Chloris ambigua'') | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=http://www.hbw.com/node/61338 | accessdate=23 October 2017 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe black-headed greenfinch was [[Species description|described]] by the French zoologist [[\u00c9mile Oustalet]] in 1896 and given the [[binomial name]] ''Chysomitris ambigua''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Oustalet | first=\u00c9mile  | author-link=\u00c9mile Oustalet | year=1896 | title=Notes sur les oiseaux recueillis dans la Yun-Nan par le Prince Henri d'Orl\u00e9an, dans le course de son dernier voyage du Tonkin aux Indes | journal=Bulletin du Museum D'Histoire Naturelle | volume=2 | pages=183\u2013187 [186] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/34214881 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | editor-last=Paynter | editor-first=Raymond A. Jnr. | year=1968 | title=Check-list of birds of the world, Volume 14 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=238 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14481439 }}</ref> In the past the black-headed greenfinch was included with the other greenfinches in the genus ''[[Carduelis]]'' but [[molecular phylogenetic]] studies have shown that the greenfinches are not closely related to the other species in the [[genus]] ''Carduelis'' and they are now placed in the resurrected genus ''[[Chloris (bird)|Chloris]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=Dario  | last2=Pr\u0177s-Jones | first2=Robert | last3=Rasmussen | first3=Pamela C. | last4=Ericson | first4=Per G.P. | year=2012 | title=The phylogenetic relationships and generic limits of finches (Fringillidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=581\u2013596 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.002 | url=http://www.nrm.se/download/18.9ff3752132fdaeccb6800010935/Zuccon%20et%20al%202012.pdf | pmid=22023825}}</ref><ref name=ioc/> The genus had originally been introduced by the French naturalist [[Georges Cuvier]] in 1800.<ref>{{cite book | last=Cuvier | first=Georges | author-link=Georges Cuvier | year=1800 | title=Le\u00e7ons d'anatomie compar\u00e9e | place=Paris | publisher=Baudouin | volume=Volume 1 | at=Table 2 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33516226 }} The year on the title page is ''An VIII''.<!--also available from Gallica: http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k1513143p/f583.image --></ref> The word ''Chloris'' is from the Ancient Greek word ''khl\u014dris'' for the [[European greenfinch]]; the specific epithet ''ambigua'' is from the Latin ''ambiguus'' for \"doubtful\".<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn= 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n44 44], 102 }}</ref>\n\nTwo subspecies are recognised:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) |editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Finches, euphonias | work= World Bird List Version 7.3 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/finches/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate=23 October 2017 }}</ref>\n* ''C. a. taylori'' ([[Norman Boyd Kinnear|Kinnear, 1939]]) \u2013 southeast Tibet\n* ''C. a. ambigua'' (Oustalet, 1896) \u2013 east and northeast Myanmar, south China, Laos and the extreme northeast India<ref>{{cite journal | last=Dalvi | first=S. | year=2013 | title=Elliot\u2019s Laughingthrush ''Trochalopteron elliotii'' and Black-headed Greenfinch ''Chloris ambigua'' from Anini, Arunachal Pradesh, India | journal=Indian Birds | volume=8 | issue=5 | page=130 | url=http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB8.5.Dalvi_ElliotsLaughingthrush.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Sharma | first1=M. | last2=Sangha | first2=H.S. | last3=Jain | first3=A. | year=2014 | title=Some noteworthy records from the Lohit Valley, eastern Arunachal Pradesh, India | journal=Indian Birds | volume=9 | issue=4 | pages=88\u201392 | url=http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB_9_4_SharmaETAL_LohtiValleyArunachalPradesh.pdf }}</ref>\n\n==References==<!-- FieldMusNatHistZoolSer18:343. -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Chloris ambigua}}\n*[http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Chloris-ambigua Xeno-canto: audio recordings of the black-headed greenfinch]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075791}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:greenfinch, black-headed}}\n[[Category:Chloris (bird)|black-headed greenfinch]]\n[[Category:Birds of Laos]]\n[[Category:Birds of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Birds of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1896|black-headed greenfinch]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Chloris ambigua, captive.jpg\n| name = Black-headed greenfinch\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |author=BirdLife International |title=''Chloris ambigua'' |volume=2016 |page=e.T22720347A94665586 |date=2016 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22720347A94665586.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Chloris\n| species = ambigua\n| authority = ([[\u00c9mile Oustalet|Oustalet]], 1896)\n| synonyms = ''Carduelis ambigua''\n}}\n\nThe '''black-headed greenfinch''' (''Chloris ambigua'') is a small [[passerine]] bird in the [[Fringillidae]] family.\nIt is found in the Chinese province of [[Yunnan]], northern [[Laos]], eastern [[Myanmar]] and adjacent areas of [[Vietnam]], [[Thailand]] and [[Northeast India]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical dry [[forest]]s and subtropical or tropical dry [[shrubland]].\n\nThe black-headed greenfinch is a medium-sized finch with a length of {{cvt|12.4|-|14|cm}}. It has a dark blackish-olive head, a pale pinkish-brown conical bill and a yellow patch on the wings. The sexes are similar.<ref name=hbw>{{cite web | last=Clement | first=P. | year=2017 | title=Black-headed Greenfinch (''Chloris ambigua'') | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=http://www.hbw.com/node/61338 | accessdate=23 October 2017 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe black-headed greenfinch was [[Species description|described]] by the French zoologist [[\u00c9mile Oustalet]] in 1896 and given the [[binomial name]] ''Chysomitris ambigua''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Oustalet | first=\u00c9mile  | author-link=\u00c9mile Oustalet | year=1896 | title=Notes sur les oiseaux recueillis dans la Yun-Nan par le Prince Henri d'Orl\u00e9an, dans le course de son dernier voyage du Tonkin aux Indes | journal=Bulletin du Museum D'Histoire Naturelle | volume=2 | pages=183\u2013187 [186] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/34214881 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | editor-last=Paynter | editor-first=Raymond A. Jnr. | year=1968 | title=Check-list of birds of the world, Volume 14 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=238 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14481439 }}</ref> In the past the black-headed greenfinch was included with the other greenfinches in the genus ''[[Carduelis]]'' but [[molecular phylogenetic]] studies have shown that the greenfinches are not closely related to the other species in the [[genus]] ''Carduelis'' and they are now placed in the resurrected genus ''[[Chloris (bird)|Chloris]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=Dario  | last2=Pr\u0177s-Jones | first2=Robert | last3=Rasmussen | first3=Pamela C. | last4=Ericson | first4=Per G.P. | year=2012 | title=The phylogenetic relationships and generic limits of finches (Fringillidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=581\u2013596 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.002 | url=http://www.nrm.se/download/18.9ff3752132fdaeccb6800010935/Zuccon%20et%20al%202012.pdf | pmid=22023825}}</ref><ref name=ioc/> The genus had originally been introduced by the French naturalist [[Georges Cuvier]] in 1800.<ref>{{cite book | last=Cuvier | first=Georges | author-link=Georges Cuvier | year=1800 | title=Le\u00e7ons d'anatomie compar\u00e9e | place=Paris | publisher=Baudouin | volume=Volume 1 | at=Table 2 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33516226 }} The year on the title page is ''An VIII''.<!--also available from Gallica: http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k1513143p/f583.image --></ref> The word ''Chloris'' is from the Ancient Greek word ''khl\u014dris'' for the [[European greenfinch]]; the specific epithet ''ambigua'' is from the Latin ''ambiguus'' for \"doubtful\".<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn= 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n44 44], 102 }}</ref>\n\nTwo subspecies are recognised:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) |editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Finches, euphonias | work= World Bird List Version 7.3 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/finches/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate=23 October 2017 }}</ref>\n* ''C. a. taylori'' ([[Norman Boyd Kinnear|Kinnear, 1939]]) \u2013 southeast Tibet\n* ''C. a. ambigua'' (Oustalet, 1896) \u2013 east and northeast Myanmar, south China, Laos and the extreme northeast India<ref>{{cite journal | last=Dalvi | first=S. | year=2013 | title=Elliot\u2019s Laughingthrush ''Trochalopteron elliotii'' and Black-headed Greenfinch ''Chloris ambigua'' from Anini, Arunachal Pradesh, India | journal=Indian Birds | volume=8 | issue=5 | page=130 | url=http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB8.5.Dalvi_ElliotsLaughingthrush.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Sharma | first1=M. | last2=Sangha | first2=H.S. | last3=Jain | first3=A. | year=2014 | title=Some noteworthy records from the Lohit Valley, eastern Arunachal Pradesh, India | journal=Indian Birds | volume=9 | issue=4 | pages=88\