e also ==\n* [[Artists with the most number-ones on the U.S. Hot 100]]\n* [[List of best-selling singles]]\n* [[List of Canadian Hot 100 number-one singles of 2016]]\n* [[List of number-one hits of 2016 (France)]]\n* [[List of UK R&B Singles Chart number ones of 2016]]\n* [[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 2016]]\n* [[List of number-one singles of 2016 (South Africa)]]\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2016 (U.S.)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|rihanna|work|Rihanna = https://genius.com/Rihanna-work-lyrics}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rihanna songs}}\n{{Drake songs}}\n\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:2016 songs]]\n[[Category:Rihanna songs]]\n[[Category:Drake (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Canadian Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Denmark]]\n[[Category:SNEP Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Portugal]]\n[[Category:South African Airplay Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK R&B Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Director X]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Boi-1da]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Drake (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by PartyNextDoor]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Rihanna]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Boi-1da]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Monte Moir]]\n[[Category:Reggae fusion songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Songs about labor]]\n[[Category:Torch songs]]\n[[Category:Dancehall songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Allen Ritter]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sevn Thomas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| language   = {{hlist|[[Jamaican Patois]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| name       = Work\n| cover      = Rihanna Work cover.png\n| alt        = Rihanna covering her face with her hands\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rihanna]] featuring [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n| album      = [[Anti (album)|Anti]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2016|1|27|mf=yes}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = December 2015\n| studio     = {{hlist|[[Westlake Recording Studios]] ([[Los Angeles]])|Sandra Gale Studios (Los Angeles)|S.O.T.A. Studios ([[Toronto]])}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Dancehall]]|[[Reggae fusion|reggae-pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=39}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Roc Nation#Artists|Roc Nation]]|Westbury Road}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[PartyNextDoor|Jahron Brathwaite]]|[[Boi-1da|Matthew Samuels]]|[[Allen Ritter]]|[[Sevn Thomas|Rupert Thomas, Jr.]]|[[Drake (musician)|Aubrey Graham]]|[[Rihanna|Robyn Fenty]]|[[Monte Moir]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Boi-1da]]|[[Noah \"40\" Shebib]]|[[Kuk Harrell]]}}\n| chronology = [[Rihanna]]\n| prev_title = [[American Oxygen]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Needed Me]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Jumpman (song)|Jumpman]]\n | prev_year  = 2015\n | title      = Work\n | year       = 2016\n | next_title = [[Summer Sixteen]]\n | next_year  = 2016\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|HL1UzIK-flA|\"Work\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Work'''\" is a song recorded by Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] for her eighth studio album, ''[[Anti (album)|Anti]]'' (2016), featuring Canadian rapper [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], the song was released as the lead single from ''Anti'' on January 27, 2016 through [[Westbury Road Entertainment|Westbury Road]] and [[Roc Nation]]. The song was written by [[PartyNextDoor]], Rihanna, Drake, [[Monte Moir]], [[Sevn Thomas|Rupert \"Sevn\" Thomas]], Allen Ritter and [[Boi-1da|Matthew Samuels]], and was produced by [[Boi-1da]], Sevn Thomas, Ritter, [[Kuk Harrell]] and [[Noah \"40\" Shebib]]. The [[dancehall]], [[Reggae fusion|reggae-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song, contains an interpolation of \"[[If You Were Here Tonight]]\" (1985) performed by [[Alexander O'Neal]]. Lyrically, the song incorporates themes of working for money, as well as discussing fragile relationships. The song is in the [[Jamaican Patois]] language and three of its writer-producers: Rupert \"Sevn\" Thomas, Matthew \"Boi-1da\" Samuels, and Jahron \"PartyNextDoor\" Brathwaite, are [[Jamaican Canadians|Jamaican-Canadians]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7616664/dancehall-charts-producers|title=Meet the Producers Who Brought Dancehall Back to the Charts In 2016|website=Billboard |access-date= March 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaicans.com/jamaican-patois-mistaken-for-gibberish-on-rihannas-new-single/|title=American Music Critics Mistake Jamaican Patois for \"Gibberish\" on Rihanna's New Single|website=Jamaicans Magazine |access-date= March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCritical response to \"Work\" was mixed upon release; critics praised its composition and Rihanna's decision to return to her earlier themes of [[Dancehall music|dancehall]] music, while others were more skeptical of the song's potential as a comeback for the singer. Critical opinion improved over time; the song was included on several year-end lists and nominated for two awards at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|59th Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]]. The song reached number one on the United States' [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, becoming Rihanna's fourteenth number-one single and making her the act with the fourth-most number-one songs on the chart (after [[The Beatles]], [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Elvis Presley]]). The song remained at the top for nine weeks. The song also peaked at number one in Canada, Brazil, Denmark, France, Netherlands and the top five of the charts in Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Ireland and Germany.\n\nThe song was accompanied by two music videos, which both premiered on February 22, 2016. The first of the two versions was directed by Rihanna's previous collaborator [[Director X]], while the second was directed by [[Tim Erem]]. The song was further promoted with live performance's at the [[2016 BRIT Awards]] which featured guest appearances from [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]], the [[2016 MTV Video Music Awards]], as well as being performed on the [[Anti World Tour]]. \"Work\" became the first dancehall song to top the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 since [[Sean Paul]]'s \"[[Temperature (song)|Temperature]]\" (2006) and was succeeded three weeks later by another dancehall song, Drake's \"[[One Dance]]\".\n\n==Background and release==\nFollowing the release of Rihanna's seventh studio album, ''[[Unapologetic]]'', and its accompanying tour, Rihanna took a step back from music.<ref name=nmeinterview>{{cite web|title=NME interview|url=https://www.nme.com/features/rihanna-exclusive-interview-i-break-the-rules-even-when-i-dont-intend-to|website=NME|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\nRihanna aimed to take a hiatus from recording music stating; \"I wanted to have a year to just do whatever I want artistically, creatively,\" Rihanna went on to state that this hiatus lasted a week and she had returned to the recording studio. Following the release of three singles in 2015\u2014\"[[FourFiveSeconds]]\" (with [[Kanye West]] and [[Paul McCartney]]), \"[[Bitch Better Have My Money]]\" and \"[[American Oxygen]]\"\u2014''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' announced that Rihanna was set to premiere a new single on January 27, 2016 at 8 am [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/27/rihanna-work-drake|title=Rihanna drops 'Work,' featuring Drake amid Anti release rumors|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Goodman|first=Jessica|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> That same day, \"Work\" premiered on several radio stations worldwide including the [[BBC Radio 1]] in the United Kingdom. Subsequently, it was made available for [[Music download|digital download]] in most countries worldwide via the [[iTunes Store]] and was added for streaming on [[Apple Music]], [[Spotify]], and [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/1/27/10840012/rihanna-drake-work-anti-new-single-listen|title= Listen to Rihanna and Drake's new single 'Work'|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Cox|first=Jamieson|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>  <!--- WRITING CREDITS FROM ITUNES METADATA --->\n\n== Writing and recording ==\n\"Work\" was written by [[PartyNextDoor]], [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[Rihanna]], [[Monte Moir]], [[Sevn Thomas|Rupert \"Sevn\" Thomas]], Allen Ritter and [[Boi-1da|Matthew Samuels]], and was produced by [[Boi-1da]], Sevn Thomas, Ritter, [[Kuk Harrell]] and [[Noah \"40\" Shebib]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.complex.com/music/2016/01/rihanna-drake-work-song-credits|title=Here's Everyone Listed in the Song Credits for Rihanna and Drake's 'Work'|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Ortiz|first=Edwin|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> In the summer of 2015, Thomas, Ritter, Boi-1da, and Martin Mason, among others, stayed at Drake's house in [[Los Angeles]] for a mid-week period. Thomas described the time spent at the home as a \"beat factory, everyone was sitting there working and collaborating with each other.\"<ref name=\"complexwriting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/01/producer-sevn-thomas-details-the-process-of-making-rihanna-and-drakes-new-single-work?sr_share=facebook|title=How a Studio Session at Drake's House in Los Angeles Turned Into Rihanna's Next Big Hit|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Frydenlund|first=Zach|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThomas created a beat which was [[dancehall]]-influenced; he later played it for Boi-1da to which he positively responded, \"We're both Jamaican-Canadian. It was just something in our DNA, so it woke him up, and we started remembering all these old dancehall songs from the '90s.\" Boi-1da came with up idea for sampling an \"old school dancehall rhythm\" and after that the chords were made with Ritter and past it, \"everything went organically\". The most recognizable sampling found in the \"Work\" [[riddim]] is from the 1998 riddim \"Sail Away\" which was produced by [[Richie Stephens (musician)|Richie Stephens]] and Mikey 2000,<ref name=\"complexwriting\"/> interpolating [[Alexander O'Neal]]'s \"[[If You Were Here Tonight]]\".\nWhen the song's music was finished, Boi-1da sent it to PartyNextDoor who wrote the lyrics, \"he's an incredible writer, and he's Jamaican as well. I think so that's how he's able to come up with those vibes and feels,\" noted Thomas. After Drake heard the song he loved it and decided to write and record a verse on it. Shortly after Braithwaite stayed at Rihanna's home in Malibu, where he played her the song.<ref name=\"complexwriting\"/>\n\nRihanna's vocals were recorded by Marcos Tovar and [[Kuk Harrell]] at the [[Westlake Recording Studios]] in Los Angeles; the latter also served as a vocal producer. Drake's vocals were recorded by Noel Cadastre and [[Noah \"40\" Shebib]] at the Sandra Gale Studios in California and the SOTA Studios in Toronto. The vocal recording was assisted by Thomas Warren, while additional vocals were provided by PartyNextDoor. Manny Marroquin [[Mixing engineer|mixed]] \"Work\" at the Larrabee Studios, while Noel \"Gadget\" Campbell and Shebib did the mixing at the Studio 360 and SOTA Studios in Toronto. The [[Mastering engineer|mastering]] was done by Chris Gehringer at the [[Sterling Sound Studios|Sterling Sound]] in New York City.<ref name=\"credits\"/> \"Work\" marks the third collaboration between Rihanna and Drake, following \"[[What's My Name (Rihanna song)|What's My Name?]]\" in 2010 and \"[[Take Care (song)|Take Care]]\" in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/62844-rihanna-and-drake-team-for-work/|title=Rihanna and Drake Team for 'Work'|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|last=Camp|first=Zoe|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Composition and lyrical interpretation ==\n\n\"Work\" is a [[dancehall]],<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21540-anti/|title=Rihanna: Anti {{!}} Album Reviews|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|last=Petrusich|first=Amanda|date=February 1, 2016|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref> [[reggae]]-[[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"reggae-pop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/01/rihanna-work-featuring-drake-bbc-radio|title=Rihanna's 'Work' Featuring Drake Debuts on BBC Radio|publisher=Fuse|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=January 27, 2016|access-date=January 27, 2016|quote=\"Work\" is a straightforward, fairly minimal reggae-pop track}}</ref> and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"capitalxtra\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalxtra.com/new-music/best-2016/rnb-songs/#oZ97PlE0APv4OAbg.97|title=The Best R&B Songs of 2016 So Far|publisher=Capital Xtra|date=November 4, 2016|access-date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> song, with a length of three minutes and thirty-nine seconds.<ref name=\"usdd\" /><ref name=\"Clean\"/> Hugh McIntyre of ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' described the song as \"quite\" [[urban music|urban]] and mixes [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] influences with \"island vibes\".<ref name=\"forbes review\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2016/01/27/rihanna-drops-new-drake-assisted-single-work/|title=Rihanna Drops New Drake-Assisted Single 'Work'|work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> Zach Frydenlund of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' wrote that the song \"is slower and very rhythmic with Rihanna showing off her vocal skills over the crafty production.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/01/rihanna-new-song-feat-drake-work|title=Rihanna and Drake Connect on New Song 'Work'|work=Complex|last=Frydenlund|first=Zach|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> The song is written in the key of [[G-sharp minor|G{{Sharp}} minor]] in [[Time signature|common time]] with a [[tempo]] of 92 beats per minute. The vocals in the song span from F{{Sharp}}<sub>3</sub> to E{{Flat}}<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0161248|title=Work|last=Fenty|first=Robyn|website=www.musicnotes.com|access-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> Alexa Camp of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called it \"an understated midtempo jam in the vein of [[Janet Jackson]]'s recent '[[No Sleeep]]', with a percolating beat, sinuous synth lines, and vocal samples stretched and pulled in a way that recalls [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]'s masterful production work on Janet's 1997 album ''[[The Velvet Rope]]''.\"<ref name=slantmag>{{cite web|last1=camp|first1=Alexa|title=Single Review: Rihanna featuring Drake, \"Work\" |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/single-review-rihanna-featuring-drake-work|website=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=January 27, 2016|date=January 27, 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'s}} Harriet Gibsone wrote: \"The glossy, modernist 'Work' skewers elements of dub and dancehall: her voice is at times [[Auto-Tune]]d, and a distant sample of what sounds a little like [[Grace Jones]]'s \"[[My Jamaican Guy]]\" haunts its empty spaces.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gibsone|first1=Harriet|title=Listen to Rihanna's Work, featuring Drake: first track from new album Anti|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/27/rihanna-work-first-track-anti-featuring-drake |website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 27, 2016|date=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'s}} Daniel Kreps wrote the song contains \"a tropical house vibe\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kreps|first1=Daniel|title=Hear Rihanna, Drake's Tropical House-Flavored 'Work'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-rihanna-drakes-tropical-house-flavored-work-20160127|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=January 27, 2016|date=January 27, 2016}}</ref> In contrary, Taj Ran from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' wrote the song \"isn't part of a new genre that many in the mainstream media are calling 'tropical house.' ''Anti''{{'s}} lead single is undeniably drenched in [[dancehall]], a genre with deep roots in Jamaica's club scene that spun off from reggae in the 1970s.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/6889497/rihanna-work-dancehall-essay | title=How Rihanna's 'Work' Made Dancehall Reign in Pop (Again) | work=Billboard | accessdate=March 2, 2016 | author=Rani, Taj}}</ref> According to ''[[The Atlantic]]''{{'}}s Spencer Kornhaber, the single has \"strangely unfinished quality\" that features its [[Verse (popular music)|verses]], [[Refrain|choruses]] and [[Bridge (music)|bridge]] fade into themselves, \"forgoing soft-to-loud explosions or exciting rhythmic changes\".<ref name=\"theatlanticreview\"/> He also noted that, Boi-1da also tries to create \"escalation\" in the song by adding additional drums for the second chorus, flutes, [[Auto-Tune|autotuned]] harmonies and back-off piano.<ref name=\"theatlanticreview\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} Jon Caramanica noted Rihanna at times \"barely even relies on words, truncating her syllables past patois to something far less exact.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/29/arts/music/review-rihanna-blissfully-adrift-juggles-styles-on-anti.html| title=Review: Rihanna, Blissfully Adrift, Juggles Styles on 'Anti' | work=The New York Times | date=January 28, 2016 | accessdate=January 28, 2016 | author=Caramanica, Jon}}</ref> Lyrically, \"Work\" is \"about working for a paycheck no matter what else is going on in your life.\"<ref name=\"theatlanticreview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/work-work-work-work-work-rihanna-drake-single-review-anti/431532/|title=How Rihanna's 'Work' Works|work=[[The Atlantic]]|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, it focuses on \"a fragile relationship\" that can be seen in the lines, \"If I get another chance to, I would never, oh never, neglect you,\" which Rihanna sings.<ref name=\"reggae-pop\"/>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n\"Work\" has received mixed reviews from critics. Editor Joe Lynch wrote that the track finds Rihanna \"reteaming with frequent collaborator/ex Drake, but that's the only predictable thing about this song\u2014while it's hardly a 180-degree turn for Rih, its minimal production subverts expectations of what you'd expect a major pop star to release when they're gearing up to drop their long-delayed new album.\"<ref name=\"billboardreview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6858259/drake-rihanna-work|title=Rihanna & Drake Reteam for 'Work'|work=Billboard|date=January 27, 2016|last=Lynch|first=Joe|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> Alexa Camp of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' wrote: \"the new track has the potential to at least partly justify the gold crown on the album's cover.\"<ref name=slantmag/> [[BET]]'s Kathy Iandoli called the song \"comfortable, but still good.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iandoli|first1=Kathy|title=Rihanna And Drake Give Us Some 'Work' off ANTI|url=http://www.bet.com/news/music/2016/01/27/rihanna-and-drake-give-us-some--work--off--anti-.html|website=[[BET]]|accessdate=January 29, 2016|date=January 27, 2016}}</ref> [[Spin (magazine)|''Spin'']]'s Brennan Carley thought Rihanna made the \"lackadaisical song gel.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.spin.com/2016/01/rihanna-drake-work-anti-lead-single-tidal/ | title=Rihanna Just Dropped the Lead 'Anti' Single, 'Work,' Featuring Drake | work=Spin| date=January 27, 2016 | accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> Other critics were more skeptical. Hugh McIntyre of ''[[Forbes]]'' wrote \"It's a well-produced song, but is it the pop hit that she needed?\"<ref name=\"forbes review\"/> [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'s Robbie Daw's review was mixed, writing \"Musically, the track is a charming, if also somewhat sparse, affair that feels like it blew in on a tropical, warm June wind and nestled up beside our ears.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7621415/rihannas-work-featuring-drake-listen-anti|title=Rihanna's 'ANTI' Single 'Work' Feat. Drake Isn't The Banger We Were Hoping For: Listen|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|last=Daw|first=Robbie|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRobin Reiff of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' wrote: \"the sheer repetition of the hook creates a built-in expiration date for when this song transitions from catchy to mildly annoying.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reiff|first1=Corbin|title=Rihanna shifts moods in the highly anticipated Anti|url=https://www.avclub.com/review/rihanna-shifts-moods-highly-anticipated-anti-231427|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=January 29, 2016|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\nTaj Rani of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' stated \"Work\" has brought the genre of dancehall to the forefront of American music (again), as it became the first dancehall song to top the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 since Sean Paul's \"[[Temperature (song)|Temperature]]\" in 2006. She opined that the song is a prime example of \"an unapologetic black woman proudly showing her heritage at a time when our politics are dominated by #BlackLivesMatter and Donald Trump's racist, xenophobic and misogynistic tirades.\" Rani continued to state that although mainstream critics are uncomfortable with Rihanna's use of patois (describing it as \"gibberish\"), she is able to display West Indian culture front and center without appropriation from mainstream culture.<ref name=\"Rani\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/6889497/rihanna-work-dancehall-essay|title=How Rihanna's 'Work' Made Dancehall Reign in Pop (Again)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Rani|first=Taj|date=March 3, 2016|accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named \"Work\" one of the 30 best songs of the first half of 2016: \"What would even you call a [[minimalist]] banger? One of America's most reliable singles artists created [[Anti (album)|an arch, moody album]] instead of a handful of chart-ready pop confections, but we still couldn't resist this barely-there tune with a beat like a dancehall wisp and lyrics like a freestyle.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/30-best-songs-of-2016-so-far-20160622|title=30 Best Songs of 2016 So Far|first=Christopher R. |last=Weingarten|publisher=Billboard|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref> \n[[The Guardian]] named it \"Best track of 2016\", writing: \"Work was off-kilter, lacked a big chorus and weaved in a dubious 80s ballad. It also clicked perfectly, a song that captured two era-defining artists and one all the more infectious for its rule-defying restraint.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2016/dec/19/best-track-of-2016-work-by-rihanna|title=Best track of 2016|first=Alexis|last=Petridis |publisher=The Guardian|date=December 19, 2016|accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\nThe British magazine ''[[NME]]'' named \"Work\" the best song of 2016 in their year-end critics' poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/list/nme-best-songs-2016-1871049|title=NME's Songs Of The Year 2016|publisher=NME|accessdate=November 26, 2016|date=November 26, 2016}}</ref> ''[[NPR]]'' and ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' both place the song at number fifteen on their year end lists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps.npr.org/best-music-2016/list/top-songs/ |title=Top 100 Songs of 2016 |publisher=NPR |date=December 6, 2006 |accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/12/top-50-songs-of-2016/5/ |title=Top 50 Songs of 2016 |publisher=Consequence of Sound |date=December 4, 2006 |accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> For ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'' it was the seventh best song of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9981-the-100-best-songs-of-2016/?page=10|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2016|publisher=Pitchfork Media|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked \"Work\" at number 25 on their \"100 Best Pop Songs of 2016\" list: \"Its hypnotic chorus burrowing its way into the year's subconscious.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2016/7617635/billboard-top-100-pop-songs-of-2016|title=Billboard's 100 Best Pop Songs of 2016: Critics' Picks|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=December 12, 2016|date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> In the annual ''[[Village Voice]]''{{'}}s Pazz & Jop mass critics poll of the year's best in music in 2016, \"Work\" was tied at number 9, with [[David Bowie]]'s \"[[Blackstar (song)|Blackstar]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/singles/2016|title=PAZZ+JOP 2016|publisher=Village Voice|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref> \n\"Work\" has been nominated for the [[Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]] and the [[Record of the Year]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref>\"Work\" won the awards for \"R&B Song of the Year\" and \"Best Collaboration\" at the 2017 iHeartRadio Music Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.iheart.com/features/iheartradio-music-awards-15/articles/15/490103/heres-the-complete-list-of-iheartradio-15616268/|title=Here's The Complete List Of #iHeartAwards Winners {{!}} iHeartRadio Music Awards {{!}} iHeartRadio|work=iHeartRadio|access-date=2017-07-18|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306212021/http://news.iheart.com/features/iheartradio-music-awards-15/articles/15/490103/heres-the-complete-list-of-iheartradio-15616268/|archive-date=March 6, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nIn France, \"Work\" peaked at number one on the chart for two weeks, becoming Rihanna's sixth number-one in the country, the second-highest amount of all time. The single also broke the record for the most streams in a single week, with 2.056 million streams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/actualite/news-101120.html|title=Double record for Rihanna, Christophe Mae back in the top 5|work=Pure Charts by Charts in France|last=Charles|first=Decant|date=February 29, 2016|accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor the issue dated February 13, 2016, \"Work\" debuted at number nine on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart. It became the 27th top-ten hit for Rihanna and 15th for Drake. With this feat, Rihanna tied [[Mariah Carey]], [[Janet Jackson]] and [[Elton John]] as the artists with the fifth-most top-ten songs on the chart.<ref name=\"workdebut\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6859557/rihanna-anti-work-billboard-charts|title=Rihanna's 'Anti' & 'Work' Blast Onto Billboard Charts|work=Billboard|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|last2=Trust|first2=Gary|date=February 1, 2016|accessdate= February 2, 2016}}</ref> The singer scored 27 top-ten singles on the Hot 100 in a span of 10 years and eight months between her first single, \"[[Pon de Replay]]\" and \"Work\", and became the fastest solo artist to reach the plateau.<ref name=\"rihannarecord\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6865869/rihanna-ties-mariah-janet-elton-hot-100-top-10s|title=Rihanna Ties Mariah, Janet & Elton for Fifth-Most Hot 100 Top 10s|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=February 2, 2016|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref> It also became Rihanna's 50th song that charted on the Hot 100.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n\"Work\" debuted at number one on the US [[Digital Songs]] chart with over 126,000 copies sold in only just over a day. It debuted at number nine on the Hot 100. \"Work\" launched at number 27 on the US [[Hot 100 Airplay (Radio Songs)|Radio Songs]] chart with 44 million audience impressions and it is her highest debut. The song was most successful on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart where it debuted atop of it, becoming Rihanna's fifth chart-topper and Drake's fourteenth.<ref name=\"workdebut\"/> The following week, \"Work\" sold an additional 156,000 copies and moved to number 7 on the Hot 100 chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6867374/zayn-pillowtalk-debuts-no-1-hot-100|title=Zayn's 'Pillowtalk' Debuts at No. 1 on Hot 100|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=February 8, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> In its third week, \"Work\" reached number four on the Hot 100 chart and became Rihanna's 20th top-five hit, tying her with [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Stevie Wonder]] as the artists with the fifth-most top-five songs on the chart<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6875473/justin-bieber-no-1-hot-100-love-yourself|title=Justin Bieber Retakes No. 1 Spot From Zayn on Hot 100|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn its fourth week, \"Work\" peaked at number one on the Hot 100 chart and became Rihanna's fourteenth number-one song in the United States. Subsequently, she became the artist with the fourth-most number-one songs on the chart following [[The Beatles]] with 20 and [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Elvis Presley]] with 18 chart toppers each.. She broke a tie with Michael Jackson, who had reached 13 chart-toppers on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 in his lifetime. Additionally, \"Work\" became Drake's second number-one single on the chart, the previous being the pair's 2010 collaboration, \"What's My Name?\". For the same issue, it rose to number 10 on the Radio Songs chart and became her 24th top-ten single, surpassing Mariah Carey's lead of 23 top-tens on that chart. The song remained at number-one on the Hot 100 for nine consecutive weeks and was unseated by [[Desiigner]]'s \"[[Panda (song)|Panda]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/04/desiigner-panda-number-one-billboard-hot-chart/|title=Desiigner's|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> As of June 2016, Work\" has sold 1,595,404 copies in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803224256/http://www.defjampromo.com/files/2009/10/BB-Digital-Songs-Chart-Wk.-Ending-6-23-16.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2018-08-03|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n\n[[File:LittleXFeb07.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Director X]] directed the first of the song's two accompanying videos.]]\n\nTwo music videos were released for the single; the first was directed by [[Director X]] who had previously worked with Rihanna on her debut video \"[[Pon de Replay]]\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Get a First Look at Rihanna and Drake's 'Work' Video|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/02/06/rihanna-drake-work-video-preview/|work=[[Rap-Up]]|accessdate=February 6, 2016|date=February 7, 2016}}</ref> while the second was directed by [[Tim Erem]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bradley|first1=Laura|title=Watch Rihanna and Drake Dance It Out in Back-to-Back Videos for \"Work\"|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2016/02/22/rihanna_and_drake_s_work_got_two_back_to_back_music_videos.html|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|accessdate=February 22, 2016|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref> Harv Glazer and Melissa Larsen served as a producer of the visual, while Daniel Bouquet and Alexi Zabes were the director of photography. Laura McMillan and Nick Rondeau were the editors of the video, while Nick Cortes served as the production coordinator. Missy Galanida, Isaac Rice and Taj Critchlow, served as the videos executive producers while Dave Hussey of Company 3 was the colorist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videostatic.com/watch-it/2016/02/22/rihanna-work-director-x-tim-erem-dir|title=WATCH IT: Rihanna f/ Drake \"Work\" (Director X, Tim Erem, dir.)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRihanna later announced its premiere date to be February 22, 2016 via her [[Twitter]] account, while also releasing a videoclip via [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HL1UzIK-flA|title=Rihanna - Work (Explicit) ft. Drake|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\nFilming of the first accompanying music video took place at the Real Jerk restaurant in [[Toronto]] on February 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drake, Rihanna spotted in Toronto shooting new video|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/drake-new-video-toronto-1.3436004|publisher=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=February 7, 2016|date=February 6, 2016}}</ref>\nDirector X stated that when filming the video they wanted to make it look like they were in a West Indian neighborhood, in a West Indian restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/6882954/director-x-rihanna-drake-work-video-interview-west-indian-culture|title=Director X Talks Creating Rihanna's 'Work' Video and Putting West Indian Culture on Full Display|publisher=}}</ref>\nThe second video for the single directed by [[Tim Erem]] was discussed between the director, Rihanna and Drake in the studio at 4 a.m., where they were attempting to come up with ideas to add a tropical vibe to their already existing footage. After thirty minutes they came up with the idea of shooting a video in a whole pink room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/6889358/director-tim-erem-rihanna-work-video-drake-dj-khaled-interview|title=Rihanna & Drake's 'Work' Video: Director Discusses Original Treatment & DJ Khaled Snapping on Set|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe first video opens with a shot of \"The Real Jerk\" carpark, in which Rihanna and Drake enter separately. The shot switches to Rihanna dancing in the nightclub, in front of a mirror. Drake enters the scene in which he raps. The video ends with credits written in a red, green and yellow typeface. The second video is shot in one piece, as it shows Rihanna and Drake in a room full of neon pink lights and styled with sofas and house plants [[aesthetics]]. \nHazel Cills of MTV noted Rihanna's and Drake's chemistry as \"playful and confrontational\", which was \"ultimately made for the viewer's pleasure\". Cills continued to state that the second video \"luxuriates in our voyeurism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2748235/video-voyeurism-rihanna-ciara-and-madonna-dance-4-u/|title=Video Voyeurism: Rihanna, Ciara, And Madonna Dance 4 U|publisher=}}</ref> Christopher Hooton from The Independent also picked upon the videos sense of [[voyeurism]] and compared the second video to Drake's previous single \"[[Hotline Bling]]\" and [[Nicki Minaj]]'s \"[[Anaconda (Nicki Minaj song)|Anaconda]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/rihanna-and-drake-drop-two-work-music-videos-separated-by-a-buffering-bar-a6891056.html|title=Rihanna and Drake drop two 'Work' music videos separated by a buffering bar|publisher=}}</ref>\nPopsugar called the songs accompanying videos \"relatively simple,\" but stated they were an \"instant classics\", while RollingStone noted the videos as being \"steamy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popsugar.co.uk/celebrity/Rihanna-Work-Video-40290586|title=Rihanna and Drake Turn the Heat Way Up in the 2-Part Video For \"Work\"|first=Maggie|last=Panos|website=POPSUGAR Celebrity UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-rihanna-drake-go-to-work-in-steamy-video-20160222|title=Watch Rihanna, Drake Go to 'Work' in New Steamy Video|first=Brittany|last=Spanos|date=February 22, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n\"Work\" was nominated for the \"Video of the Year\" award as the 2016 [[BET Awards]], as well as being nominated for the \"Best Female Video\" award as the 2016 [[MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 BET Awards Nominations|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/05/20/bet-awards-2016-nominations/|work=Rap-Up.com|date=May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2910480/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-2016-vmas/ | title=Rihanna Is Your 2016 Vanguard | work=MTV News | date=August 11, 2016 | accessdate=August 11, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Time Magazine]]'' listed the video at number eight on their Top 10 Pop Music Videos of 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4568524/top-10-pop-music-videos-2016/ |title=Top 10 Pop Music Videos of 2016 |publisher=Time Magazine |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> while ''[[Pitchfork Media]]'' placed it at number twenty-five on their list of The Best Music Videos of 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9979-the-best-music-videos-of-2016/ |title=The Best Music Videos of 2016 |publisher=Pitchfork Media |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> As of June 2018, the video has received over 1.0 billion views on [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"youtube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HL1UzIK-flA|title=Rihanna - Work (Explicit) ft. Drake|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Performances and remixes ==\nRihanna performed \"Consideration\" with [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] and \"Work\" with Drake live for the first time at the [[2016 Brit Awards]] on February 24, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/brit-awards-2016-drake-join-rihanna-first-live-performance-work-londons-o2-arena-1545733|title=Brit Awards 2016: Drake to join Rihanna for first live performance of Work at London's O2 Arena?|publisher=International Business Times|date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> It was Rihanna's first appearance to promote the album with a live performance.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Augustin|first1=Camille|title=SZA & Drake Join Rihanna For A Performance At The 2016 Brit Awards|url=http://www.vibe.com/2016/02/rihanna-brit-awards-2016-performance-drake/|accessdate=July 25, 2016|work=Vibe|date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> \"Work\" was also included on her [[Anti World Tour]] (2016), as well as being performed along with ''[[Too Good]]'' at [[OVO Fest]] with Drake in [[Toronto]] on July 31, 2016. Rihanna also performed the song at the [[2016 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/67860-mtv-vma-2016-watch-rihanna-perform-four-career-spanning-medleys/|title=MTV VMA 2016: Watch Rihanna Perform Four Career-Spanning Medleys - Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2016, rapper [[ASAP Ferg]] released his remix of \"Work\" via [[SoundCloud]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/02/rihanna-new-song-work-remix-featuring-asap-ferg|title=Listen to A$AP Ferg's Remix of Rihanna's \"Work\"|work=Complex|last=Mench|first=Chris|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=February 14, 2016}}</ref>\nOn February 17, 2016, Nigerian artist [[Burna Boy]] released his remix of \"Work\" along with a lyric video.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/02/22/burna-boy-rihanna-drake-work-remix | title=Burna Boy Gave Rihanna's \"Work\" An Awesome Nigerian Remix | publisher=[[The Fader]] | date=February 22, 2016 | accessdate=March 9, 2016 | author=Kameir, Rawiya}}</ref>\nOn March 6, 2016 American rapper [[Lil Mama]], released a remix of the song. Lil Mama's version featured the same production and chorus but was accompanied by new rap verses. Lil Mama's version was also released with a video, in which she recreated the original video along with choreographed dance moves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/03/06/lil-mama-remixes-rihanna-drake-work/|title=Lil Mama Remixes Rihanna & Drake's 'Work'|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2016, [[DJDS]] released an '80s-inspired remix via Soundcloud.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/03/08/djds-remix-rihanna-work|title=Listen To DJDS' Remix Of Rihanna's \"Work\"|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\nOn March 19, 2016, Work (Remixes) EP was officially released via Tidal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://listen.tidal.com/track/58402690|title=Try the TIDAL Web Player|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Including [[R3hab|R3HAB]] REMiX (Extended Remix and Extended Instrumental), [[Burns (musician)|Burns]]' Late Night Rollin' Remix, [[Bad Royale]] Remix (Bad Royale Remix), and [[Lost Kings]] Remix (and Extended Remix). American producers [[Ookay]] & Yultron released a remix of the song as well, giving it a hybrid [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]-inspired beat. The remix was released via SoundCloud on Yultron's page.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/yultron-vip/riri-work-feat-drizzy-ookay-x-yultron-remix/|title=RiRi - Werk Feat. Drizzy (Ookay x Yultron Remix)|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=\"usdd\" /><ref name=\"Clean\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/work-feat.-drake-single/id1078761736|title=Music \u2013 Work (feat. Drake) \u2013 Single by Rihanna|publisher=iTunes Store (US)|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n| title1 = Work\n| note1 = featuring Drake\n| length1 = 3:39\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Remixes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://listen.tidal.com/album/58402689|title=Try the TIDAL Web Player|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| title1 = Work\n| note1 = [[R3hab]] Remix) (featuring Drake\n|