35 | doi=10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2005.12.013| pmid = 16647594 }}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 23450547 | doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004001.pub3 | volume=2 | issue=2 | title=Spinal cord stimulation for non-reconstructable chronic critical leg ischaemia. | year=2013 | journal=Cochrane Database Syst. Rev. | pages=CD004001 | author=Ubbink DT, Vermeulen H}}.\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Yampolsky C, Hem S, Bendersky D | year = 2012 | title = Dorsal column stimulator applications | url = | journal = Surg. Neurol. Int. | volume = 3 | issue = Suppl 4| pages = S275\u201389 | doi = 10.4103/2152-7806.103019 | pmid = 23230533 | pmc = 3514915 }}\n* {{Cite journal  | last1 = Yelnik | first1 = AP. | last2 = Simon | first2 = O. | last3 = Parratte | first3 = B. | last4 = Gracies | first4 = JM. | title = How to clinically assess and treat muscle overactivity in spastic paresis. | journal = J. Rehabil. Med. | volume = 42 | issue = 9 | pages = 801\u20137 |date=Oct 2010 | doi = 10.2340/16501977-0613 | pmid = 20878038 }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Zafonte R, Lombard L, Elovic E | year = 2004 | title = Antispasticity medications: uses and limitations of enteral therapy | url = | journal = Am. J. Phys. Med. Rehabil. | volume = 83 | issue = 10 Suppl| pages = S50\u2013S58 | doi=10.1097/01.phm.0000141132.48673.fa| pmid = 15448578 }}\n<!-- safety do not delete brackets--> }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1525-1403 Neuromodulation: Technology at the Neural Interface]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151208075107/http://www.newswise.com/articles/1st-global-guidance-announced-on-neurostimulation-for-pain Neuromodulation Appropriateness Consensus Committee (news release)]\n\n[[Category:Implants (medicine)]]\n[[Category:Pain]]\n[[Category:Physical psychiatric treatments]]\n[[Category:Neurological disorders]]\n[[Category:Neurophysiology]]\n[[Category:Neuropsychology]]\n[[Category:Neurotechnology]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNon-invasive Prescription Therapy:Fix PMC warnings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuromodulation_(medicine)"}
{"title_page": "C/1989 X1", "text_new": "{{Infobox Comet\n| name=C/1989 X1 (Austin)\n| image= Comet Austin develops an ion tail (Eso9004a).jpg\n| caption        = The comet on February 24, 1990, by [[La Silla Observatory]], [[ESO]]\n| discoverer     = Rodney Austin\n| discovery_date = 6 December 1989\n| designations= 1990 V, 1989c1\n| perihelion=0.3497735 AU\n| inclination=58.95559\u00b0\n| eccentricity=1.0002278\n| last_p= 9 April 1990\n}}\n\n'''C/1989 X1 (Austin)''' (old-style designations 1990 V and 1989c1) was a comet discovered by [[New Zealand]] amateur Rodney R. D. Austin on December 6, 1989. The comet at discovery was predicted to become easily visible by [[naked eye]] in spring 1990, however it failed to become that bright.\n\n== Observations ==\nRobert Austin discovered the comet on December 6, 1989 through an 8-inch [[Schmidt-Newtonian telescope]], and it was his third comet discovery.<ref name=\"Machholz94\">{{cite journal |last1=Machholz |first1=Don E. |title=Comet Austin 1989c1: what went wrong? |journal=JALPO |date=April 1994 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=171\u2013176 |url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/pdf/1994JALPO..37..171M |language=en |issn=0039-2502}}</ref> By the time of its discovery, it was already obvious that it must be an large object, as the comet was still more than 350 million kilometres (2.42 AU) from the [[Sun]] and yet it was so bright that it was seen as an 11th magnitude object (that is, 1/100 as bright as what can be perceived with the unaided eye).<ref name=\"ESO9004\"/>\n\nMore observations were soon made, establishing the comet's orbit, and it was found that it would pass through its perihelion (the point of its orbit where it is closest to the Sun) on 9 April 1990 at a distance of about 53 million kilometres, inside the orbit of [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], the planet closest to the Sun, and it would come within 38 million kilometres of the Earth on May 25. The orbit indicated that the northern hemisphere after 20 April 1990 could be seen low above the NW horizon, just after sunset, and even better above the NE horizon, shortly before sunrise, and it was expected to develop an easily observable tail which would be a grand celestial view.<ref name=\"ESO9004\">{{cite web|title=ESO - eso9004 - Comet Austin Develops a Long Tail|publisher=ESO|url=http://www.eso.org/public/news/eso9004/|accessdate=2010-01-11}}</ref> Its high eccentricity, above 1, indicated that it was a dynamically new object from the [[Oort cloud]].<ref name=\"Machholz94\"/>\n\nThe comet was at 83 degrees elongation from the Sun at discovery and nearly circumpolar for the south hemisphere. The comet slowly moved northwards and passed the [[Celestial equator|equator]] on March 21, 1990, however its elongation from the Sun, around 25 degrees, meant it was difficult to observe. After the perihelium the comet would start to move gradually away from the Sun and at the time of the closest approach to Earth would be 100 degrees away from the Sun, at the constellation of [[Aquila (constellation)|Aquila]] and moving southward.<ref name=\"Machholz94\"/>\n\nA long ion tail was observed on late February 1990.<ref name=\"ESO9004\"/> However, as the comet approached to perihelium the rate of brightening started to slow when it was 1.56 to 1.27 AU away from the Sun and although activity increased again in April, the comet ended up about 6 magnitudes dimmer than expected at maximum brightness, being dimmer than magnitude 2, with most obervators reporting a maximum brightness between +4 and +6. The comet was visible with naked eye between May 5 and May 25, 1990, before fading below naked eye visibility.<ref name=\"Machholz94\"/>\n\n== Scientific results ==\n[[File:Comet Austin jet (Eso9003f).jpg|thumb|A jet observed by [[New Technology Telescope|NTT]] on February 9, 1990.]]\nThe spectrum of the comet upon discovery showed the presence of [[hydroxyl]] emission and continuum from the dust, however the presence of dust was noted to be unusually low. The spectrum also revealed the presence of  gases like [[cyanide]], [[CO2]]+, and [[diatomic carbon]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Comet Austin |url=https://archive.stsci.edu/iue/gallery/pr_caus.html |website=archive.stsci.edu |date=8 April 1998}}</ref> Futher observations of the spectrum of the comet revealed the presence of the forbidden [[oxygen]] line (1128 \u00c5) and the absence of features attributed to [[helium]], [[argon]] and diatomic [[nitrogen]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=GREEN |first1=J. C. |last2=CASH |first2=W. |last3=COOK |first3=T. A. |last4=STERN |first4=S. A. |title=The Spectrum of Comet Austin from 910 to 1180 A |journal=Science |date=25 January 1991 |volume=251 |issue=4992 |pages=408\u2013410 |doi=10.1126/science.251.4992.408}}</ref> The millimetre spectrum of the comet, by the radiotelescope of [[Institut de radioastronomie millim\u00e9trique|IRAM]], showed the presence of hydrogen cyanide, [[formaldehyde]], [[hydrogen sulphide]] and [[methanol]], and was the first time the latter two were observed in the spectrum of a comet.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bockel\u00e9e-Morvan |first1=Dominique |last2=Colom |first2=Pierre |last3=Crovisier |first3=Jacques |last4=Despois |first4=Didier |last5=Paubert |first5=Gabriel |title=Microwave detection of hydrogen sulphide and methanol in comet Austin (1989c1) |journal=Nature |date=March 1991 |volume=350 |issue=6316 |pages=318\u2013320 |doi=10.1038/350318a0}}</ref>\n\nThe comet was imaged in [[infrared]] by the [[Cosmic Background Explorer|COBE satellite]] on May 6, 1990 and revealed the presence of a dust tail 6 degrees long at 12 and 25 micrometres. The tail exhibited complex structure that was attributed to the variations of the dust production rate of the comet, which was estimated to be {{val|510|510|205}} kg/s. It was estimated that the nucleus of the comet was covered manily by particles measuring 20 micrometers in diameter.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lisse |first1=C. M. |last2=Freudenreich |first2=H. T. |last3=Hauser |first3=M. G. |last4=Kelsall |first4=T. |last5=Moseley |first5=S. H. |last6=Reach |first6=W. T. |last7=Silverberg |first7=R. F. |title=Infrared observations of Comet Austin (1990 V) by the COBE/Diffuse Infrared Background Experiment |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |date=September 1994 |volume=432 |pages=L71 |doi=10.1086/187514}}</ref> The comet was also observed by the Golden Gopher [[infrared camera]] with 8 to 12 micrometer filters, the first time this camera was used to observe a comet. The images didn't show the presence of jets or shells and the coma appeared slightly elongated. It was estimated by these observations that the comet lost about a tonne of material every second on May 6, and fell to 570 kilos per second on May 12.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fomenkova |first1=M.N. |last2=Jones |first2=B. |last3=Pi\u00f1a |first3=R.K. |last4=Puetter |first4=R.C. |last5=McFadden |first5=L.A. |last6=Abney |first6=F. |last7=Gehrz |first7=R.D. |title=Thermal-Infrared High-Resolution Imaging of Comet Austin |journal=Icarus |date=December 1993 |volume=106 |issue=2 |pages=489\u2013498 |doi=10.1006/icar.1993.1187}}</ref>\n\nObservations of the comet with [[polarimeter]] revealed the presence of jets and shells, common characteristics of a comet. It was also observed that the dust particles of the comet had higher [[albedo]] than usual.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eaton |first1=N. |last2=Scarrott |first2=S. M. |last3=Gledhill |first3=T. M. |title=Polarization studies of comet Austin |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |date=15 September 1992 |volume=258 |issue=2 |pages=384\u2013386 |doi=10.1093/mnras/258.2.384}}</ref> Other photopolarimetric observations estimated the size of the main dust particles to be 0.1 to 0.5 \u03bcm. The cyanide and diatomic carbon had polarisation close to the predicted one, but the triatomic carbon had lower polarisation than the predicted one.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Joshi |first1=U. C. |last2=Sen |first2=A. K. |last3=Deshpande |first3=M. R. |last4=Chauhan |first4=J. S. |title=Photopolarimetric studies of comet Austin |journal=Journal of Astrophysics and Astronomy |date=September 1992 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=267\u2013277 |doi=10.1007/BF02702294}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 1990, as the tail of comet Austin passed in front of the [[quasar]] [[3C 441]], it enhanced the [[Scintillation (physics)|scintillations]] in radio waves.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Janardhan |first1=P |last2=Alurkar |first2=SK |last3=Bobra |first3=AD |last4=Slee |first4=OB |title=Enhanced Radio Source Scintillation due to Comet Austin (1989c1) |journal=Australian Journal of Physics |date=1991 |volume=44 |issue=5 |pages=565 |doi=10.1071/PH910565 |url=https://www.publish.csiro.au/ph/pdf/PH910565}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{JPL Small Body|C/1989 X1}}\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-data_query?bibcode=1994JALPO..37..171M&link_type=ARTICLE&db_key=AST&high=;filetype=.pdf Comet Austin 1989c1: What went wrong?]\n\n{{Comets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:C 1989 X1}}\n[[Category:Non-periodic comets]]\n[[Category:Hyperbolic comets]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1989|19891206]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Comet\n| name=C/1989 X1 (Austin)\n| image= Comet Austin develops an ion tail (Eso9004a).jpg\n| caption        = The comet on February 24, 1990, by [[La Silla Observatory]], [[ESO]]\n| discoverer     = Rodney Austin\n| discovery_date = 6 December 1989\n| designations= 1990 V, 1989c1\n| perihelion=0.3497735 AU\n| inclination=58.95559\u00b0\n| eccentricity=1.0002278\n| last_p= 9 April 1990\n}}\n\n'''C/1989 X1 (Austin)''' (old-style designations 1990 V and 1989c1) was a comet discovered by [[New Zealand]] amateur Rodney R. D. Austin on December 6, 1989. The comet at discovery was predicted to become easily visible by [[naked eye]] in spring 1990, however it failed to become that bright.\n\n== Observations ==\nRobert Austin discovered the comet on December 6, 1989 through an 8-inch [[Schmidt-Newtonian telescope]], and it was his third comet discovery.<ref name=\"Machholz94\">{{cite journal |last1=Machholz |first1=Don E. |title=Comet Austin 1989c1: what went wrong? |journal=JALPO |date=April 1994 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=171\u2013176 |url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/pdf/1994JALPO..37..171M |language=en |issn=0039-2502}}</ref> By the time of its discovery, it was already obvious that it must be an large object, as the comet was still more than 350 million kilometres (2.42 AU) from the [[Sun]] and yet it was so bright that it was seen as an 11th magnitude object (that is, 1/100 as bright as what can be perceived with the unaided eye).<ref name=\"ESO9004\"/>\n\nMore observations were soon made, establishing the comet's orbit, and it was found that it would pass through its perihelion (the point of its orbit where it is closest to the Sun) on 9 April 1990 at a distance of about 53 million kilometres, inside the orbit of [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], the planet closest to the Sun, and it would come within 38 million kilometres of the Earth on May 25. The orbit indicated that the northern hemisphere after 20 April 1990 could be seen low above the NW horizon, just after sunset, and even better above the NE horizon, shortly before sunrise, and it was expected to develop an easily observable tail which would be a grand celestial view.<ref name=\"ESO9004\">{{cite web|title=ESO - eso9004 - Comet Austin Develops a Long Tail|publisher=ESO|url=http://www.eso.org/public/news/eso9004/|accessdate=2010-01-11}}</ref> Its high eccentricity, above 1, indicated that it was a new object from the [[Oort cloud]].<ref name=\"Machholz94\"/>\n\nThe comet was at 83 degrees elongation from the Sun at discovery and nearly circumpolar for the south hemisphere. The comet slowly moved northwards and passed the [[Celestial equator|equator]] on March 21, 1990, however its elongation from the Sun, around 25 degrees, meant it was difficult to observe. After the perihelium the comet would start to move gradually away from the Sun and at the time of the closest approach to Earth would be 100 degrees away from the Sun, at the constellation of [[Aquila (constellation)|Aquila]] and moving southward.<ref name=\"Machholz94\"/>\n\nA long ion tail was observed on late February 1990.<ref name=\"ESO9004\"/> However, as the comet approached to perihelium the rate of brightening started to slow when it was 1.56 to 1.27 AU away from the Sun and although activity increased again in April, the comet ended up about 6 magnitudes dimmer than expected at maximum brightness, being dimmer than magnitude 2, with most obervators reporting a maximum brightness between +4 and +6. The comet was visible with naked eye between May 5 and May 25, 1990, before fading below naked eye visibility.<ref name=\"Machholz94\"/>\n\n== Scientific results ==\n[[File:Comet Austin jet (Eso9003f).jpg|thumb|A jet observed by [[New Technology Telescope|NTT]] on February 9, 1990.]]\nThe spectrum of the comet upon discovery showed the presence of [[hydroxyl]] emission and continuum from the dust, however the presence of dust was noted to be unusually low. The spectrum also revealed the presence of  gases like [[cyanide]], [[CO2]]+, and [[diatomic carbon]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Comet Austin |url=https://archive.stsci.edu/iue/gallery/pr_caus.html |website=archive.stsci.edu |date=8 April 1998}}</ref> Futher observations of the spectrum of the comet revealed the presence of the forbidden [[oxygen]] line (1128 \u00c5) and the absence of features attributed to [[helium]], [[argon]] and diatomic [[nitrogen]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=GREEN |first1=J. C. |last2=CASH |first2=W. |last3=COOK |first3=T. A. |last4=STERN |first4=S. A. |title=The Spectrum of Comet Austin from 910 to 1180 A |journal=Science |date=25 January 1991 |volume=251 |issue=4992 |pages=408\u2013410 |doi=10.1126/science.251.4992.408}}</ref> The millimetre spectrum of the comet, by the radiotelescope of [[Institut de radioastronomie millim\u00e9trique|IRAM]], showed the presence of hydrogen cyanide, [[formaldehyde]], [[hydrogen sulphide]] and [[methanol]], and was the first time the latter two were observed in the spectrum of a comet.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bockel\u00e9e-Morvan |first1=Dominique |last2=Colom |first2=Pierre |last3=Crovisier |first3=Jacques |last4=Despois |first4=Didier |last5=Paubert |first5=Gabriel |title=Microwave detection of hydrogen sulphide and methanol in comet Austin (1989c1) |journal=Nature |date=March 1991 |volume=350 |issue=6316 |pages=318\u2013320 |doi=10.1038/350318a0}}</ref>\n\nThe comet was imaged in [[infrared]] by the [[Cosmic Background Explorer|COBE satellite]] on May 6, 1990 and revealed the presence of a dust tail 6 degrees long at 12 and 25 micrometres. The tail exhibited complex structure that was attributed to the variations of the dust production rate of the comet, which was estimated to be {{val|510|510|205}} kg/s. It was estimated that the nucleus of the comet was covered manily by particles measuring 20 micrometers in diameter.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lisse |first1=C. M. |last2=Freudenreich |first2=H. T. |last3=Hauser |first3=M. G. |last4=Kelsall |first4=T. |last5=Moseley |first5=S. H. |last6=Reach |first6=W. T. |last7=Silverberg |first7=R. F. |title=Infrared observations of Comet Austin (1990 V) by the COBE/Diffuse Infrared Background Experiment |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |date=September 1994 |volume=432 |pages=L71 |doi=10.1086/187514}}</ref> The comet was also observed by the Golden Gopher [[infrared camera]] with 8 to 12 micrometer filters, the first time this camera was used to observe a comet. The images didn't show the presence of jets or shells and the coma appeared slightly elongated. It was estimated by these observations that the comet lost about a tonne of material every second on May 6, and fell to 570 kilos per second on May 12.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fomenkova |first1=M.N. |last2=Jones |first2=B. |last3=Pi\u00f1a |first3=R.K. |last4=Puetter |first4=R.C. |last5=McFadden |first5=L.A. |last6=Abney |first6=F. |last7=Gehrz |first7=R.D. |title=Thermal-Infrared High-Resolution Imaging of Comet Austin |journal=Icarus |date=December 1993 |volume=106 |issue=2 |pages=489\u2013498 |doi=10.1006/icar.1993.1187}}</ref>\n\nObservations of the comet with [[polarimeter]] revealed the presence of jets and shells, common characteristics of a comet. It was also observed that the dust particles of the comet had higher [[albedo]] than usual.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eaton |first1=N. |last2=Scarrott |first2=S. M. |last3=Gledhill |first3=T. M. |title=Polarization studies of comet Austin |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |date=15 September 1992 |volume=258 |issue=2 |pages=384\u2013386 |doi=10.1093/mnras/258.2.384}}</ref> Other photopolarimetric observations estimated the size of the main dust particles to be 0.1 to 0.5 \u03bcm. The cyanide and diatomic carbon had polarisation close to the predicted one, but the triatomic carbon had lower polarisation than the predicted one.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Joshi |first1=U. C. |last2=Sen |first2=A. K. |last3=Deshpande |first3=M. R. |last4=Chauhan |first4=J. S. |title=Photopolarimetric studies of comet Austin |journal=Journal of Astrophysics and Astronomy |date=September 1992 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=267\u2013277 |doi=10.1007/BF02702294}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 1990, as the tail of comet Austin passed in front of the [[quasar]] [[3C 441]], it enhanced the [[Scintillation (physics)|scintillations]] in radio waves.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Janardhan |first1=P |last2=Alurkar |first2=SK |last3=Bobra |first3=AD |last4=Slee |first4=OB |title=Enhanced Radio Source Scintillation due to Comet Austin (1989c1) |journal=Australian Journal of Physics |date=1991 |volume=44 |issue=5 |pages=565 |doi=10.1071/PH910565 |url=https://www.publish.csiro.au/ph/pdf/PH910565}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{JPL Small Body|C/1989 X1}}\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-data_query?bibcode=1994JALPO..37..171M&link_type=ARTICLE&db_key=AST&high=;filetype=.pdf Comet Austin 1989c1: What went wrong?]\n\n{{Comets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:C 1989 X1}}\n[[Category:Non-periodic comets]]\n[[Category:Hyperbolic comets]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1989|19891206]]\n", "name_user": "C messier", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C/1989_X1"}
